author: Charis Chang
title: Young, NSW terror raids: 42-year-old man arrested over terrorism offences
text:
THE Australian Federal Police has arrested a 42-year-old man in the NSW regional town of Young for alleged terrorism offences. 
Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull said the charges were not related to a planned terror attack, but said the individual was alleged to have sought to advise ISIL on how to develop high-tech weapons capability.
The man is believed to have been an electrician working in Young, which is located just two hours outside of Canberra.
AFP Commissioner Andrew Colvin said the 42-year-old man was arrested and would be charged with a number of offences.
This will include two serious foreign incursion offences under the Commonwealth criminal code, which carry a maximum penalty of life imprisonment.
He said the man was an Australian-born man and was an Australian citizen.
The AFP will allege the man used the internet to perform services for Islamic State from Australia.
Firstly, by researching and designing a laser warning device to help warn against incoming guiding munitions used by coalition forces in Syria and Iraq.
Secondly, that he has been researching, designing and modelling systems to assist Islamic State’s efforts to develop their own long-range guided missile capabilities.
Federal Justice Minister Michael Keenan said the arrest today was the result of an 18-month-long operation.
“It reminds us that whether you are in a capital city planning an attack on home soil or whether you are in a small country town, trying to assist the terrorist state in the Middle East, you will get caught,” Mr Keenan said.
